# EtherHiding to ClickFix on new-blog.artlist[.]io

Last updated: 2026-07-13

This report reconstructs the browser, JavaScript, PowerShell, archive-delivery, DLL-loading, nested-decoder, and native C2 chain.

## Executive summary

On July 13, 2026, `new-blog.artlist[.]io` served an obfuscated script at the top of its main HTML. The primary `artlist[.]io` site was clean at the time. The script decoded into an EtherHiding loader that queried a Polygon smart contract, recovered the next-stage host, and injected a script from `auth-code-check[.]info`.

The next stage is a ClickFix payload. It presents a fake reCAPTCHA overlay, blocks common inspection shortcuts, copies a PowerShell command to the clipboard, and tells the visitor to paste it into Windows Terminal. The PowerShell chain downloads a password-protected ZIP, extracts it with a staged copy of `7z.exe`, searches for `fdupdate.exe`, attempts to start it, and calls a post-attempt marker.

A fresh replay showed that delivery remained active. In the first replay, `/p/<token>` returned `200` and the old archive token returned `410 Gone` one second later. A fresh token then delivered the 31 MB `fdupdate.zip` archive before any request to `/p/<token>`. The results indicate that delivery state may depend on the token, request history, source address, `vid`, or timing.

The Windows payload enters through a local DLL chain loaded by the signed StruSoft/FEM-Design updater `fdupdate.exe`. That chain reaches `LibBind.dll`, which starts a loader thread, reads an encrypted slice from `Stream.Toolkit.dat`, XOR-decodes it, copies it into memory allocated by `TBFVSS_DLL_SRV_64.dll`, marks the region executable, and runs it through an `EnumTimeFormatsEx` callback. The decoded payload resolves APIs manually and contains VM-detection logic, AMSI/.NET strings, Run-key persistence strings, and file-extension targets including `bak`, `db`, `bin`, `dat`, `raw`, and `pak`.

The chain nests several more stages. The `Stream.Toolkit.dat` shellcode parses `Face.dat` and decodes a script/config record plus an `act.exe` PE record. The `act.exe` loader decrypts an embedded ZIP into raw x64 code. That code XOR-decodes a PE32+ DLL at raw offset `0xc48`, length `0x873c00`, using byte mask `0x43 ^ (i & 0xff)`, maps it in memory, and calls its entry point.

The final DLL supports browser-store collection and protected outbound transfer, resumable file upload and download, process inventory and termination, shell commands, SOCKS bridging, remote-desktop control, service setup, keylogging, desktop/video capture, and remote-process manipulation. It also contains private-key-capable PFX export code with no mapped activation path.

The affected subdomain runs WordPress. The same script appeared at the top of the HTML across multiple pages, indicating a sitewide injection. Its consistent placement fits a shared WordPress component such as the active theme, a plugin, or code attached to an early rendering hook.

